I snapped these photos of @littlebrother_nc (@rapperbigpooh and @phontigallo) back in October 2019 when they came thru Denver. I kinda forgot to share them. 

The first time I had ever heard of Little Brother was back in 2005 when they dropped The Minstrel Show. I was 22 at the time and doing a tour in Iraq. The PX out in Balad was getting all the new albums that summer. A lot of classic shit was dropping around that time— Late Registration, Be, Thug Motivation 101, A.W.O.L., Diary of a Summer, Monkey Barz— but The Minstrel Show was something special. It was something I hadn’t really heard before. That album is one of the few I consider perfect from top to bottom, and it got me thru some of my toughest days in the desert. Aight peace #hiphop50 #theyshootn

Introducing "When Heaven Scrapes the Pavement" -- my photo contribution to the "Desert Rider: Dreaming in Motion" exhibit opening this Sunday at the @denverartmuseum. It's an honor to have this photo placed alongside the work of legendary Denver artists like Carlos Frésquez and Daniel Salazar. 

I have been documenting the lowrider community in Denver close to a decade now. In that time, I have been fortunate to forge relationships that will last a lifetime, while also accumulating a large collection of photos. A few of my images were considered for this exhibit before we ultimately decided on this one. While many of my photos are untitled, I knew I needed one for this photo that told a story. 

I wanted to bridge the gap between lowrider culture and spirituality — not that there is a huge space between those two to begin with. The son of two South American immigrants, I grew up in the Catholic Church, and while I ultimately abandoned all religious ideologies, I remained open to the ethereal aspects of life and to those things that keep us spiritually connected. The lowrider community, to me, is one of those elements. 

Parking lots become churches on the weekends; the stories told on stained glass windows unfold similarly on candy paint and chrome; we take communion from the taquero; we say "peace be with you" through daps and hugs; we confess our sins from the night before over a cold Modelo; we two-step to hymns by Zapp & Roger. It's at the weekend kick-back or at the show and shine when heaven scrapes the pavement. 

Go peep this image and much more at the Denver Art Museum, running July 9 through September 24.

The 1948 Chevy Fleetline (left) is owned by Joe O’Connell from Ranflitas CC, and the 1962 Chevy Impala SS (right) is owned by Brian Casias from Citywide CC.

Lowriders at the @denverartmuseum — it’s about damn time. It was beautiful to see the city show up. Everywhere I looked yesterday, I saw smiling faces, dancing and family and friends enjoying themselves. Thank you to everyone who’s congratulated and shown love to my piece inside the museum. I’m humbled and I think it finally hit me yesterday. Getting to hear all the personal stories about the neighborhood where my photo was made definitely touched my spirit. I’m not from here, but this has been my home for over a decade now. Thank you for embracing me. I’m gonna keep doing my best to make y’all proud 🫀 #theyshootn

When I was asked to be a part of the “Desert Rider: Dreaming in Motion” exhibit, I was excited to continue the work I’ve started of showcasing different members of Denver’s lowrider community. When I found out my work would be displayed next to that of Daniel Salazar and Carlos Frésquez, I felt honored and grateful. It’s because of artists like them that I have the opportunities to show my photography on a larger scale. I remember seeing Daniel’s “Westside Dreams” at different places around Denver and hoping that one day I would get to make a photo that was 10% as iconic as that. So it’s wild to see my photo hanging directly across from Daniel’s at the Denver Art Museum — a space that has a history of not including artists like us.

Originally, the plan was for me to have two black-and-white photos displayed for the Desert Rider exhibit, but the museum ended up deciding to go with one color print. I had already printed the two black-and-white ones, so it was dope to be able to give these prints away to @bribricasias and @rega1292. “Eastside Communion” and “Sacred Chrome” represent a part of Denver that not a lot of folks, mainly outsiders, know exist. Being from California, I was ignorant to the rich lowriding culture in Denver when I first settled down here 13 years ago. What I ended up finding reminded me of home. Thanks again to the people who’ve stood in front of my camera or who’ve let me shoot their rides, and trusted that I would represent them and their stories as honest as I could.

Thanks to @xencs333 for taking the photo of Daniel and I at the opening. Last slide contains my three selections for the Desert Rider: Dreaming in Music playlist. Had to throw in some of my favorite music to cruise to #theyshootn

“I Am Auraria” — Jay and Rick are two members of the displaced Auraria community in Denver. Here they hold a photo of them and their classmates from their early school years at St. Elizabeth’s Church, located on the Auraria Campus.

In 1965, a flood devastated the Auraria neighborhood in Denver, which had a largely-Latino population at the time. Because of the flood damage, the City of Denver began looking into redeveloping the site, which led to the establishment of Metropolitan State College, and ultimately the clearing out of Denver’s oldest neighborhood to transform it into a modern urban campus.

The federal government put up funds, which were matched by a bond approved by Denver voters, to buy the land and relocate Auraria’s residents. Many Aurarians tried resisting the displacement, however, they ultimately failed and were forced to move from the neighborhood they called home. Relocations were completed by 1972, and the new campus was completed in 1976. When you walk through the modern-day Auraria campus, you’ll see a few buildings still standing from the original neighborhood. 

Join us next Wednesday, August 23, 5pm-7pm, at the Auraria Library for the opening of “I Am Auraria”, a Museum of Memory exhibit by @historycolorado. Through this exhibit, hundreds of families who were displaced from the original Auraria neighborhood will be able to tell their stories on their terms. 

As a former graduate of Metro State, I’m honored to be a small part of this project. I’m thankful to the families I was able to photograph for putting their trust in me for the short time we were able to spend together. To learn more, hit the link in my stories.

Recently, I worked with the @denverbasicincomeproject (DBIP). What DBIP does is deliver direct cash assistance to Denver’s unhoused with no strings attached. 

I photographed and connected with some of DBIP’s clients and was inspired to hear their stories of how these cash payments drastically improved their lives. From finding housing and employment, to reconnecting with loved ones, to getting clean and sober.

DBIP just released the Quantitative Interim Report conducted by DU’s Center for Housing and Homelessness Research showing incredible results for folks who’ve participated in the program for at least six months. 

To see the report’s finding and how you can get involved, visit denverbasicincomeproject.org. You can also call your city council and demand that DBIP be included in this year’s budget amendments. 

If they have $2 million to spend on pickleball, they can help fund this life-changing program for another year. Hold this new mayor accountable.

And thank you to @itsnoneyabiz and his son for letting us use his award-winning lowrider trike. See y’all this weekend #theyshootn
Scenes from Día de los Muertos at La Raza Park #theyshootn

“Con flores nos reciben y entre ellas nos despiden” -an installation by Yours Truly

For the last decade, I’ve been fortunate to be able to create art alongside some of my favorite people. This project represents 10 years of labor and love. These Muertos celebrations started off small, as a way to honor those we’ve lost along the way. Our circle grew over the years, and while our objective remained, it became clear that these gatherings were building and engaging community. It became an outlet for us to create meaningful art in remembrance of who and where we came from. Putting them on hasn’t always been easy, but it’s always been rewarding.

You can now see this 8’ x 24’ installation hanging in front of @culturachocolate (3742 Morrison Road) for the @muertosenwestwood event going down this entire weekend. 

I hope to see all my peoples tomorrow who don’t usually get to make it to this side of town. It’s been a rough few weeks in this shitty world we live in, but I challenge you to come out and celebrate life and death in a beautiful way.

My deepest gratitude goes out to every model, makeup artist, designer, car/bike owner and anyone else who ever assisted on one of these shoots. This project doesn’t happen without your skills and contributions. Special thanks to @xencs333 and the Sun, @3rd_dvision, @anthonymvze, and the good people of @culturachocolate, @revision_coop and @hechoenwestwood for your help in making this installation possible.

This piece is dedicated to everyone we’ve lost; to the people of Denver; and to the neighborhood of Westwood.

📸 by @xencs333
